Univariate Exploration¶

Distrubution of Learning time¶

In [280]:
sns.set(style='white',color_codes=True);
sns.displot(st.MMINS, kde=True, color = 'tomato',bins=80,alpha=0.7);
plt.xlim([0,800]);
plt.xlabel("Learning time (minutes per week)");
plt.ylabel('Frequency');
plt.title('Distrubution of Learning time',fontsize=15);
sns.despine(trim=True ,offset=10)
sns.set_style('ticks')

We can see that there many spikes in the distrubution but it fairly follows a normal distrubution pattern

In what month to have your baby if you want his chances of being smart high ?¶

In [268]:
months = {1:'Jan',2:'Feb',3:"Mar",4:'Apr',5:'May',6:'Jun',7:'Jul',8:'Aug',9:'Sep',10:'Oct',11:'Nov',12:'Dec'}
best_months = st[st.GRADE > 0]
best_months.ST03Q01= list(map(lambda num: months[num] if num in months else None,best_months.ST03Q01)) # converting months from numbers to names
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6));
best_months.ST03Q01.value_counts().plot(kind = 'bar',color = sns.color_palette()[4]);
plt.title("Birth month of best scoring students");
plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel('Students born');
sns.despine(trim=True ,offset=5)
sns.set_style('ticks')

From the bar chart shown, we can conclude the a big portion of the number of kids who score grades higher than 2 are born in January

Does being interested in a subject, make you enjoy it ?¶

In [181]:
math_interest_joy = st[['ST29Q06','ST29Q04']]
math_interest_joy.dropna(inplace = True)
math_interest_joy_agree = math_interest_joy.query("('Agree' in ST29Q06 or 'Strongly agree' in ST29Q06) and ('Agree' in ST29Q04 or 'Strongly agree' in ST29Q04)")
math_interest_joy_disagree = math_interest_joy.query("('Agree' in ST29Q06 or 'Strongly agree' in ST29Q06) and ('Disagree' in ST29Q04 or 'Strongly disagree' in ST29Q04)")
math_interest_joy_agree['ratio'] = 'Interested and enjoys math'
math_interest_joy_disagree['ratio'] = "Interested but doesn't enjoy math"
result=pd.concat([math_interest_joy_agree,math_interest_joy_disagree])

Bivariate Exploration¶

In [263]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,7))
sns.pointplot(data=st,x='ST29Q06',y='MMINS',order=['Strongly disagree','Disagree','Agree','Strongly agree'],color=sns.color_palette()[9]);
plt.xlabel('Levels of liking math',fontsize=17)
plt.ylabel('Learning time (minute per week)',fontsize=17);
plt.title('Relationship between the level of liking math and learning time',fontsize=17)
sns.despine(trim=True ,offset=1)
sns.set_style('ticks')

It is obvious that the more the students like math, the more they will spend more time learning

The relationship between gender and learning time¶

In [260]:
plt.figure(figsize = (17,6));
sns.set(style="white", color_codes=True)
sns.violinplot(data = st, x ='ST04Q01',y = 'MMINS',color = sns.color_palette()[3]);
plt.xlabel('Gender',fontsize=17);
plt.ylabel('Learning time (minute per week)',fontsize=17);
plt.title('Relationship between gender and learning time of math',fontsize=17)
sns.despine(trim=True ,offset=1);
sns.set_style('ticks');

Very fortunatly, There doesn't seem to be a big difference between the learning time of either males or females. Though, some outliers in the male group suggest that males tend to spend more time learning than females.

Does the level of education of the parents affects the learning time of their children ?¶

In [251]:
plt.figure(figsize = (20,7));
sns.lineplot(data = st, x ='PARED',y = 'MMINS',color = sns.color_palette()[2]);
plt.xlabel('Parental level of education (years)',fontsize=20);
plt.ylabel('Learning time of (minutes per week)',fontsize=20);
plt.title('Parental Level of education against Learning time of their children',fontsize=20);
sns.despine(offset=1);
sns.set_style('ticks');

There is an unexpected pattern that appears to exit here; Many fluctuations occur and surprisingly at about 10-12 years of parental education,children tend to spend less time learning than those whom parents have lower level of education, We can confirm this by looking at the bar chart below

In [252]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,7))
sns.barplot(data=st,x='PARED',y='MMINS',color=sns.color_palette()[9]);
plt.xlabel('Parental level of education (years)',fontsize=20);
plt.ylabel('Mean of the Learning time (minutes per week)',fontsize=20);
plt.title('Parental Level of education against Learning time of their children',fontsize=20);
sns.despine(trim=True ,offset=1);
sns.set_style('ticks');

Taking a look at the bar chart, we can see that the unexpected drop exists when the parental level of education is at 10.5.

From the scatter plot shown, There doesn't seem to be a relation between the wealth of the family and the learning time of the children

From the results, We can interpret that the sex doesn't have a major effect combined with wealth on the learning time as almost the two charts are identical
